"## Abstract\nAccurate light field depth estimation in non-Lambertian scenes remains a fundamentally challenging task, as complex material reflections severely violate multi-view consistency assumptions. Conventional epipolar plane image (EPI)-based paradigms critically fail in these regions due to the lack of distinguishing physical priors between true depth structures and specular or scattering artifacts. To address this limitation, we propose a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model coupled with a novel Multi-scale Angular Cost Volume Network (MACVO-Net). Specifically, we pioneer the introduction of MRI-inspired k-space frequency analysis into light field imaging, utilizing medium and angular direction masks to mathematically decouple material reflection types. We develop an adaptive dual-modal energy optimization strategy, guided by a Geometry Consistency Descriptor (GCD) and the Segment Anything Model (SAM), to precisely suppress non-Lambertian interference. Furthermore, our MACVO-Net constructs an explicit all-view (81-view) cost volume and employs a multi-scale U-Net architecture, treating flat cost responses as explicit uncertainty priors to guide depth propagation during the guided training process. Experimental results demonstrate that our physics-driven approach significantly outperforms existing methods, achieving up to a 320% improvement in local texture energy contrast within specular regions while substantially reducing overall depth estimation errors. Ultimately, this work establishes a robust and physically interpretable framework that successfully breaks through the persistent accuracy bottleneck of non-Lambertian light field depth estimation.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian, Dual-mask physical model, Cost volume network, k-space frequency analysis"